-- tBibliography -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe essays in this groundbreaking book explore the meanings of manhood in Japan from the seventeenth to the twenty-first centuries. Recreating Japanese Men examines a broad range of attitudes regarding properly masculine pursuits and modes of behavior. It charts breakdowns in traditional and conventional societal roles and the resulting crises of masculinity. Contributors address key questions about Japanese manhood ranging from icons such as the samurai to marginal men including hermaphrodites, robots, techno-geeks, rock climbers, shop clerks, soldiers, shoguns, and more. In addition to bringing historical evidence to bear on definitions of masculinity, contributors provide fresh analyses on the ways contemporary modes and styles of masculinity have affected Japanese men’s sense of gender as authentic and stable.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMasculinityzJapan. 0aMenzJapanxIdentity. 0aMenzJapan. 0aSex rolezJapan. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aAlgoso, Teresa A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCondry, Ian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrühstück, Sabine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrühstück, Sabine, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGerteis, Christopher, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGill, Tom, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHiroko, Nagano, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aManzenreiter, Wolfram, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNapier,